<p><strong>Black Salamander (<em>Aneides flavipunctatus</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Plethodontidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Aneides flavipunctatus</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>Black Salamander<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p> The Black Salamander has a body length between 2-3¾ inches and a total length of up to 5 inches. Its dorsal coloration varies greatly depending on locality. For example, it is uniformly black or black with small white flecks in the southern part of its range, and black frosted with gray, olive, or green in the redwood country of Mendocino and Humboldt counties. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.californiaherps.com/salamanders/pages/a.f.niger.html">California Herps</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>This salamander inhabits mixed deciduous woodlands, coniferous forest, and coastal grasslands. It is chiefly ground dwelling and is found under rocks, along streams, under legs, bark, boards, and other objects. Diet consists of small invertebrates. Females lay eggs in the summer.</p>
